data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active - condition check on each element
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *both* values, e.g. `"Expected: 3, Actual: 1"`
- **`Assert.IsTrue` with a message** — when you must use it, add a description so failures are diagnosable
- **`Any()` over `Single()`** — `Single()` throws an unhandled exception if missing, which shows as an error rather than a test failure

**Other `CollectionAssert` options worth knowing:**

```csharp
// Verify no nulls in the list
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// Verify all items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Verify exact contents (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, users);

// Verify same contents regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, users);

// Verify a specific item is present
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer `Assert.AreEqual` / `CollectionAssert` over `Assert.IsTrue` — they produce self-describing failure messages.
